| Powers Reserved to States or People       | Limits federal government powers                                                            | Tenth                       |

## Conclusion

The Bill of Rights protects citizens by explicitly enumerating fundamental rights and civil liberties, thereby limiting the power of the federal government and, through incorporation, state governments as well. It guarantees freedoms essential to democratic governance, such as speech, religion, and fair legal procedures, and serves as a critical check against government overreach. Its enforcement mechanisms ensure that violations of these rights are subject to legal consequences, preserving the rule of law and individual liberty. The Bill of Rights remains indispensable to the American legal and political system, safeguarding the freedoms that define the nation.

